    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-12-21T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-12-21T05:00:00-05:00" n="789"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d789">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94112/287: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-12-21T19:00:00+09:00"
                            >December 21, 1939—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 21—1:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>697. Our 694, December 20, 2 p.m.<note n="22" xml:id="d789fn22">Not printed; it
                        gave a paraphrase of a telegram from the British Ambassador in Japan to his
                        Government. The substance of this telegram is given in the British Embassy’s
                            <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> of December 26, <ref
                            target="#pg_797">p. 797</ref>.</note> I refer to the third of the five
                    points enumerated to my British colleague<note n="23" xml:id="d789fn23">Sir
                        Robert L. Craigie, British Ambassador in Japan.</note> by the Vice
                        Minister<note n="24" xml:id="d789fn24">Masaynki Tani.</note> which are to be
                    discussed in connection with the opening of the Yangtze. Information was brought
                    to me recently that Jardine, Matheson<note n="25" xml:id="d789fn25">British
                        shipping firm in China.</note> have been in touch with a number of Japanese
                    interests concerning a Japanese proposal for pooling foreign shipping on the
                    Yangtze, and that the former were interested in the proposals, especially if
                    American shipping is brought into the pool. I reported the matter by despatch in
                    view of assurances by Craigie that he had advised <pb facs="0800" n="796"
                        xml:id="pg_796"/> Jardine against present participation, but reference by
                    Tani to the project indicates that it has assumed important proportions.</p>
                <p>My despatch will go forward in the pouch leaving December 23.<note n="26"
                        xml:id="d789fn26">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sent to the Department, repeated to Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
